{{More footnotes|date=July 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Asian immigrants to Sweden | population = 273,787<ref name="Popcz"/> | popplace = [[Stockholm]] {{·}} [[Gothenburg]] {{·}} [[Malmö]] | langs = [[Swedish language|Swedish]] {{·}} [[languages of Asia]] | rels = [[Christianity]] {{·}} [[East Asian religions]] ([[Buddhism]]) {{·}} [[Hinduism]] {{·}} [[Islam]] |related-c = [[Ethnic groups in Asia]] }} '''Asian immigrants to Sweden''' are citizens and residents of [[Sweden]] who were born in or have ancestry from nations in [[Asia]]. Over the period 2000-2016, Sweden's population of Asian descent grew by 223,253<ref name=SCB/>{{disputed inline|date=February 2017}}, mainly due to immigration.
Many immigrants to Sweden are from Asia. [[Thailand]], [[China]], [[Vietnam]], [[Mongolia]], [[Korea]], [[Philippines]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], [[Afghanistan]], [[India]], and [[Pakistan]], are the most represented countries.
==Demographics== According to [[Statistics Sweden]], as of 2016, there is a total 273,787 residents of Sweden who hold citizenship from countries in Asia.<ref name="Popcz">{{cite web|title=Foreign citizens by country of citizenship, sex and year|url=http://www.statistikdatabasen.scb.se/pxweb/en/ssd/START__BE__BE0101__BE0101F/UtlmedbR/table/tableViewLayout1/?rxid=b83e5bbd-958a-4655-aa40-486ba2ca09a3|publisher=Statistics Sweden|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>
According to Statistics Sweden, as of 2016, there is a total of 8,541 foreign-born children and young adults aged 0-21 who are [[adoption|adopted]] in Sweden. Of these individuals, the most common countries of birth are [[China]] (3,977), [[South Korea]] (1,735), [[Colombia]] (1,438), [[Vietnam]] (1,241), and [[India]] (1,017).<ref name="Popap">{{cite web|title= Adopted children and young persons, number by sex, age, country of birth and year|url=http://www.statistikdatabasen.scb.se/pxweb/en/ssd/START__LE__LE0102__LE0102I/BarnAdoption/table/tableViewLayout1/?rxid=a8cb32e8-c0b7-4d51-9a96-119a3090e94c|publisher=Statistics Sweden|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>
